{"id": "d60a364ef49848e9979f33503abc6327", "timestamp": "2025-12-10 21:59:38", "name": "Scientist1", "content": "This is a timely and challenging problem, especially as single-view 3D reconstruction moves toward real-world applications where object orientation is unpredictable. Current methods often struggle with pose variability because the latent representations they learn are entangled with viewpoint-dependent features—this leads to poor generalization when the test-time orientation differs from training data.\n\nOne promising direction is to design a framework that explicitly disentangles pose from shape in the latent space. We could leverage geometric priors—such as symmetry, reprojection consistency, or equivariant neural networks under rotation groups (e.g., SO(3)-equivariant CNNs or steerable CNNs)—to build intrinsic, pose-invariant descriptors. For instance, instead of encoding shape relative to the observed viewpoint, we could align the input to a canonical pose implicitly through a pose-estimation bottleneck or via self-supervised alignment using differentiable rendering.\n\nAnother angle is contrastive learning in the latent space: by applying random rotations to the same object and enforcing similarity in shape representation while allowing pose codes to vary, we can encourage invariance. This could be combined with a pose-aware decoder that re-applies the estimated orientation during reconstruction, effectively factorizing shape and pose.\n\nA key innovation would be to achieve this without requiring multi-view supervision or 3D ground truth during training—relying instead on single-view images with implicit supervision through reconstruction loss via differentiable rendering. If we can achieve robust pose invariance in a fully unsupervised or self-supervised manner, it would significantly advance the scalability of 3D reconstruction models to open-world settings.\n\nWhat do you think about combining SO(3)-equivariant feature extractors with a canonical-space VAE? This might allow us to map arbitrary views into a rotation-invariant latent shape code while factoring out the pose, enabling more consistent reconstructions across orientations.", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[97mScientist1\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "6e5329eb499a473da4b7335d7a5b5334", "timestamp": "2025-12-10 21:59:41", "name": "Scientist1", "content": "The discussion focuses on improving single-view 3D reconstruction by addressing pose variability through disentangling shape and pose in the latent space. Key ideas include using geometric priors (e.g., symmetry, reprojection consistency) and SO(3)-equivariant networks to create pose-invariant shape representations. A proposed solution involves combining SO(3)-equivariant feature extractors with a canonical-space VAE to achieve rotation-invariant shape encoding and explicit pose factorization. The approach aims to be self-supervised, relying on single-view images and differentiable rendering without multi-view or 3D ground truth, enhancing generalization to unseen orientations.", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[97mScientist1\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "55326157ed3c4204a2f6b855cf9356fb", "timestamp": "2025-12-10 21:59:41", "name": "Scientist1", "content": "[retrieved]:", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[97mScientist1\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "ff9c11ad251046928eb8ba547e8aef2e", "timestamp": "2025-12-10 21:59:54", "name": "Scientist1", "content": "Building on the direction we've been exploring—particularly the disentanglement of shape and pose using geometric priors and SO(3)-equivariance—I’d like to refine our research focus toward a more structured and scalable framework for **learning pose-invariant latent representations in single-view 3D reconstruction**, with an emphasis on **robustness to arbitrary object orientations**.\n\nOne key challenge in current methods is that even when using equivariant networks, the latent space can still entangle pose and shape due to ambiguities inherent in single-view observations. For example, a car viewed from behind might be misinterpreted as a different instance if the model hasn’t explicitly learned to normalize orientation. To address this, I propose we investigate a **canonicalization-by-synthesis** framework that combines **SO(3)-equivariant feature learning** with a **self-supervised pose normalization module** operating entirely in latent space.\n\nHere’s how it could work:  \nWe design a network where the encoder produces both a **pose-equivariant latent vector** (transforming predictably under rotation) and a **pose-invariant shape code**. The equivariant component allows us to \"rotate\" the inferred shape in the latent space, while the invariant component captures intrinsic geometry. Then, through differentiable rendering and reprojection consistency across synthetic viewpoints, we enforce that rotating the shape code should yield views consistent with the input under plausible transformations.\n\nCrucially, instead of relying on explicit pose labels or multi-view supervision, we can use **cycle-consistency losses**: given an input image, we predict a canonical shape and a relative pose; then, by applying the inverse rotation in the latent space and re-rendering, we should recover an image similar to the original. This creates a self-supervised loop that encourages the model to factorize appearance into stable, canonicalized shape representations regardless of input orientation.\n\nMoreover, we can enhance robustness by incorporating **symmetry-aware constraints** during training—especially useful for categories like chairs or airplanes—where certain axes of rotation leave the object visually unchanged. By learning to detect and exploit such symmetries implicitly, the model avoids overfitting to arbitrary canonical frames.\n\nThis approach would push beyond current state-of-the-art methods like HoloGAN or Self-Supervised Shape Reconstruction via E(3)-CNNs by unifying **equivariant representation learning**, **implicit canonicalization**, and **differentiable rendering** within a single, end-to-end trainable pipeline that requires only single-view images at training time.\n\nThe potential impact is significant: enabling reliable 3D reconstruction from arbitrarily oriented inputs without requiring pose annotations or multi-view correspondences opens up applications in robotics, AR/VR, and autonomous systems where viewpoint control is limited.\n\nI’m curious—how do others feel about prioritizing **implicit canonical space alignment via cycle-consistent rendering** as our core innovation? Are there specific object categories or symmetry priors we should bake in early to boost convergence?", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[97mScientist1\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "5f3fda8c38c24e00b8156015004d95b4", "timestamp": "2025-12-10 22:00:00", "name": "Scientist1", "content": "**Summary of Scientist1's contribution:**\n\nScientist1 proposes refining the team’s focus toward a **structured, self-supervised framework for learning pose-invariant latent representations** in single-view 3D reconstruction, emphasizing **robustness to arbitrary object orientations**. To overcome latent space entanglement due to single-view ambiguity, they introduce a **canonicalization-by-synthesis** approach that combines:\n\n- **SO(3)-equivariant feature learning** for predictable latent transformations under rotation,  \n- A **self-supervised pose normalization module** operating in latent space,  \n- **Cycle-consistency losses** via differentiable rendering to enforce reprojection accuracy without multi-view or pose supervision,  \n- **Symmetry-aware constraints** to improve convergence and avoid bias in canonical frame selection.\n\nThe key innovation is an **end-to-end, single-image-trained pipeline** that unifies equivariant representation learning, implicit canonicalization, and differentiable rendering—advancing beyond methods like HoloGAN or E(3)-CNNs.\n\n**Proposed next steps/decisions for team input:**  \n- Prioritize **implicit canonical space alignment via cycle-consistent rendering** as the core technical contribution.  \n- Determine whether to **incorporate category-specific symmetry priors** (e.g., chairs, airplanes) early in training to boost stability and convergence.", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[97mScientist1\u001b[0m"}
